data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — all three APIs (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) are gone in .NET 6+.

---

## Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. There is no way to forcibly kill a managed thread. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

---

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    // Option A: Work does NOT need a CancellationToken (fire-and-forget on timeout)
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws TimeoutException if the timeout expires (.NET 6+)
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            cts.Cancel();
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ag) when (ag.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ag.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Option B (preferred): Work cooperates with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

## What changed and why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `Start` | `Task.Run(...)` | Uses the thread pool; same semantics, less overhead |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `Task.WaitAsync(timeout)` | Returns a faulted/timed-out task instead of a bool |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative — requests cancellation rather than forcing it |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The new exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed; cancellation is voluntary |

---

## Key pitfalls

1. **Option A doesn't truly stop the work.** `cts.Cancel()` only sets a flag — if `work` ignores it, the delegate keeps running on a thread-pool thread. This is the fundamental paradigm shift: cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.

2. **Option B is strongly preferred.** Pass `CancellationToken` into the work and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints:
   ```csharp
   var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
   {
       foreach (var item in items)
       {
           token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
           Process(item);
       }
       return items.Count;
   }, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
   ```

3. **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks.

4. **`Thread.Sleep` won't respond to cancellation.** If your work calls `Thread.Sleep(ms)`, replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so the sleep wakes immediately on cancel.

5. **Truly uncooperative code** (third-party libs, native calls) cannot be cancelled this way. The only option is to move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout.
